This paper is about named entity recognition, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the computer science category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper proposes a new method for recognizing nested named entities, which involves training a neural model and designing an objective function. This suggests that the paper could also be relevant to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper involves decoding methods for inference, which could relate to the sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper presents experimental results on specific datasets, including ACE-2004, ACE-2005, and GENIA, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the sub-category of neural networks (cs.NE).
